A '''bed burial''' is a type of [[burial]] in which the deceased person is buried in the ground, lying upon a bed. It is a burial custom that is particularly associated with high status women during the early [[Anglo-Saxon]] period (7th century), although excavated examples of bed burials are comparatively rare.
==Anglo-Saxon bed burials== [[File:Saxon Princess Kirkleatham.jpg|right|thumb|220px|Replica of the "Saxon Princess" bed burial at the [[Street House Anglo-Saxon cemetery]]]] A number of early Anglo-Saxon bed burials, almost all dating to the 7th century, have been found in England, predominantly in the southern counties of [[Cambridgeshire]], [[Suffolk]] and [[Wiltshire]], but single examples have also been found in [[Derbyshire]] and [[North Yorkshire]]. The beds used in these burials were made of wood, and although none have been fully preserved, their presence can be inferred from the presence of iron fixtures and fittings, such as nails, [[Cleat (nautical)|cleats]], [[grommet]]s, brackets, [[Headboard (furniture)|headboard]] mounts and railings, that outline the rectangular shape of the bed in the grave.<ref name="Williams 2006 31">{{harvnb|Williams|2006|p=31}}</ref><ref name="antiquity-2008"/><ref>{{Cite journal | last=Eagles | first=Bruce | title=Review of [[George Speake|G. Speake]], A Saxon bed burial on Swallowcliffe Down| journal=[[Wiltshire Archaeological and Natural History Magazine]] | issn=0262-6608 | volume=84 | year=1991 | pages=163–164 }}</ref> However, in some cases it is not clear whether the iron fixtures found in a grave come from a bed or a coffin.
The majority of the Anglo-Saxon bed burials are for young women, and many of the burials include items of jewellery and other [[grave goods]] that indicate that the dead person must have been wealthy and of high status during life. The high quality of the gold jewellery found in the [[Loftus, North Yorkshire#Anglo-Saxon royal burial site|bed burial at Loftus]] in Yorkshire suggests that the occupant of the grave may have been a princess.<ref name="redcar-cleveland-2011-05-04">{{Cite news | title=Anglo-saxon princess' treasure set to go on show | url=http://www.redcar-cleveland.gov.uk/pressrel.nsf/published/may_2011_anglo_saxon_princess_treasure_set_to_go_on_show | date=4 May 2011 | publisher=Redcar and Cleveland News }}</ref> On the other hand, some of the young women buried on their beds have [[pectoral cross]]es or other Christian emblems buried with them ([[Ixworth#History|Ixworth]],<ref name=ixworthcross>{{PastScape|mnumber=385467 |mname=|accessdate=2013-01-22}}</ref> Roundway Down, Swallowcliffe Down, [[Trumpington bed burial|Trumpington]]), which has suggested the possibility that they may have been [[abbess]]es, who in the early Anglo-Saxon period were recruited from noble families.<ref>{{harvnb|Blair|2005|p=230}}</ref>
In addition to laying the deceased on a bed, some of the bed burials exhibit other features that mark them out as special, and relate them to [[ship burial]]s, such as the bed being placed in a chamber (Coddenham, Swallowcliffe Down), or a [[Tumulus|barrow]] being raised above the grave (Lapwing Hill, Swallowcliffe Down).<ref>{{harvnb|Lee|2007|p=82}}</ref> In at least two sites (Loftus and Trumpington), a ''[[grubenhaus]]'' (sunken floored building) has been excavated close to the bed burial, and it is possible that the deceased was laid out in the ''grubenhaus'' before burial so that mourners could pay their respects to her.<ref name="antiquity-2008">{{Cite journal | last1=Sherlock | first1=Steve | last2=Simmons | first2=Mark | title=A seventh-century royal cemetery at Street House, north-east Yorkshire, England | journal=Antiquity | issn=0003-598X | volume=82 | issue=316 | date=June 2008 | url=http://antiquity.ac.uk/projgall/sherlock/index.html }}</ref><ref name="miar-report-2011">{{Cite web | title=Archaeology at Cambridge 2010–2011 | url=http://www.mcdonald.cam.ac.uk/reports/miar-report-2011.pdf | publisher=Cambridge University | year=2011 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130925231643/http://www.mcdonald.cam.ac.uk/reports/miar-report-2011.pdf | archivedate=2013-09-25 | df= }}</ref>
The complex and elaborate funeral practices that must have been associated with a bed burial have been well described by archaeologist [[Howard Williams (archaeologist)|Howard Williams]]:
{{quote|The artefacts, body and grave would have interacted to create a complex sequences of practices and performances in the funeral. We can imagine the digging of the grave, perhaps the lining of the grave with timber shorings, and perhaps a temporary shelter over the grave in the hours or days until the body is ready for burial. We then have the lowering of a bed into the grave, followed by the clothed body together with a set of discrete deposits. Each would have required persons approaching the grave and passing them down to those in the grave itself with the body. Finally, after the funeral had approached completion, the grave would have been back-filled and the mound raised.<ref name="Williams 2006 31">{{harvnb|Williams|2006|p=31}}</ref>}}
Interring the deceased on a bed suggests that sleep was seen as a metaphor for death.<ref name="Williams 2006 31">{{harvnb|Williams|2006|p=31}}</ref> Furthermore, the [[Old English]] word ''leger'' (modern English ''lair''), literally meaning a "place where one lies", was used to refer to both beds and graves in [[Old English literature]], which emphasizes the symbolic equivalence of the bed and the grave.<ref name="cam-2012-03-16">{{Cite web | last1=Dickens | first1=Alison | last2=Lucy | first2=Sam | title=Mystery of Anglo-Saxon teen buried in bed with gold cross | url=http://www.cam.ac.uk/research/news/mystery-of-anglo-saxon-teen-buried-in-bed-with-gold-cross/ | date=16 March 2012 | accessdate=2012-03-16 }}</ref>
===List of Anglo-Saxon bed burials=== About a dozen Anglo-Saxon bed burials, as well as several possible bed burials, have been excavated from the 19th century onwards, as listed in the table below.
