{{Use American English|date=September 2014}}

{{Use MDY dates|date=February 2015}}

[[File:Walker County ID photo fx Recon 007b.jpg|thumb|The [[Walker County Jane Doe]]'s case is one of Texas' most-known unidentified person cases]]

In Texas, there are a number of murder victims, in the category of [[unidentified decedent]]s, whose identities have yet to be found. In most of these cases, their murderer or murderers have also gone undiscovered.

{{anchor|Harris County John Doe (1973)}}

==Harris County John Doe (1973)==
{{external media	
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [https://identifyus.org/en/medias/full/19977 Reconstructions and clothing]
| image2 = [http://doenetwork.org/cases/images/1010UMTX_boots.jpg Boots]
}}

A white or [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Hispanic]] male between 15 and 18 years old was found buried in a [[Harris County, Texas|Harris County]] boat shed in August 1973.

This youth is the only still-unidentified victim of serial killer [[Dean Corll]], who, together with two teenage accomplices, killed at least 28 boys and young men between 1970 and 1973.<ref name="Christian">{{cite web|last=Christian|first=Carol|title=40 years after Houston serial killings, one victim still unidentified|url=http://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/houston/article/40-years-after-Houston-serial-killings-one-4686772.php|accessdate=18 April 2014|date=25 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=John Doe 1973|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1109009|publisher=[[Center for Missing and Exploited Children]]|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> This decedent was between 5 feet 2 and 5 feet 7 inches tall, had brown hair, and is believed to have worn striped swim trunks, boots, and a shirt displaying a [[peace symbol]]. These items were found near his body.<ref name=bone>{{cite news|last1=Olsen|first1=Lise|title='Detective' will exhume bodies in victim identity hunt|url=http://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/Detective-will-exhume-bodies-in-victim-identity-1691577.php#ixzz1Nx3nb9AT|accessdate=8 December 2014|work=Houston Chronicle|date=30 May 2011}}</ref>

He had received good dental care, and had never received any [[teeth fillings]] in his lifetime. It is known that he suffered from a mild form of [[spina bifida]].<ref name="Case File 1010UMTX">{{cite web|title=Case File 1010UMTX|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/1010umtx.html|publisher=The Doe Network|accessdate=21 May 2014}}</ref> [[DNA profiling|DNA]] testing conducted in 2008 did not match any [[missing person]] report.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 4547|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/4547|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=6 January 2015|date=15 October 2008}}</ref>

A [[forensic science|forensic examination]] of the boy's remains, in addition to the [[Circumstantial evidence|circumstantial fact]] that he was buried between two identified victims of Dean Corll (killed in August 1971 and July 1972), indicated that he was most likely murdered in either 1971 or 1972.

=="Orange Socks"==

{{main|Orange Socks}}

A 15- to 30-year-old woman discovered in [[Georgetown, Texas]], on Halloween of 1979. Her body was naked save for a pair of orange socks. She had been killed by strangulation, and had contracted [[salpingitis]] in her lifetime.<ref name="Case File: 33UFTX">{{cite web| title=Case File: 33UFTX| url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/33uftx.html| publisher=[[The Doe Network]]| accessdate=20 March 2014}}</ref>

==Walker County Jane Doe==

{{main|Walker County Jane Doe}}

A teenage female whose body was discovered approximately six hours after she died on October 31 or November 1, 1980. [[Henry Lee Lucas]] has been named as a potential suspect in this case,<ref>{{cite web| title=Walker Texas Jane Doe November 1980|website=canyouidentifyme.org| url=http://www.canyouidentifyme.org/WalkerTexasJaneDoeNovember1980| accessdate=May 12, 2014| year=2012}}</ref> although a bite mark found upon the decedent's shoulder was inconsistent with Lucas's dentistry.<ref name="Case File: 91UFTX">{{cite web| title=Case File: 91UFTX| url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/91uftx.html| publisher=The Doe Network| accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref>

She was estimated to be between the ages of 14 and 18 years old with brown hair and brown or hazel eyes. She had claimed to a waitress that she was 19 but the waitress did not believe her. She was described as wearing a yellow pullover sweater and red heeled sandals. She was also wearing a square or rectangular pendent necklace with a smokey blue or brown stone. The necklace was found on the body and the shoes were nearby but none of her clothing was located. 

When her body was found it was determined she had only been dead for several hours. She had been viciously sexually assaulted with a large foreign object. A truck driver had seen her body on the north bound side of highway 45 about a mile north of The Hitchin Post truck stop. 

The waitress who spoke to her claimed the girl told her she was from the Aransas Pass/Rockport area but no missing persons were reported in that area around the time of her death.

==Harris County Does (1981)==

{{main|Harris County Does}}

A young man and woman who were found in January 1981. They were killed approximately two months earlier and left in Houston.<ref name=doenetf>{{cite web|title=Case File 476UFTX|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/476uftx.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=25 October 2014}}</ref>

{{anchor|Harris County Jane Doe (1985)}}

==Harris County Jane Doe (1985)==

[[File:32UFTX Reconstruction 005a.jpg|thumb|left|150px|The Harris County Jane Doe, found in 1985, had a tattoo of the letter "V" on her arm]]

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://doenetwork.org/cases/images/32UFTX.jpg Sketch]
| image2 = [http://doenetwork.org/cases/images/32UFTX1.jpg Jewelry]
}}

On August 12, 1985, the body of a Hispanic female aged between 16 and 35 was found inside a vacant store. Her body was discovered alongside that of a man who was identified as Thomas Rodriguez, and her death had occurred hours prior to her discovery. She was between five feet and five feet two inches, and weighed approximately 120 to 140 pounds. Other distinctive details regarding this decedent include two sets of distinctive earrings she had worn which contained beads and shells, a tattoo of the letter 'V' on her upper left arm, and a scar resulting from her [[gallbladder]] being removed. A necklace with an arrowhead and turquoise stone design was also found on the girl's neck. It is unknown how both victims were placed at the scene.<ref name="Case File 32UFTX">{{cite web|title=Case File 32UFTX|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/32uftx.html|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=27 May 2014}}</ref>

{{anchor|Parker County John Doe}}

==Parker County John Doe==

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://api.missingkids.org/photographs/NCMU1104373c1.jpg NCMEC reconstruction]
| image2 = [https://identifyus.org/en/medias/full/8724 3D reconstruction]
}}

On October 27, 1985, the skeleton of a male between fourteen and twenty-one was found in Springtown, Parker County, Texas.<ref>{{cite web|title=Unidentified Person's Details|url=http://www.txdps.state.tx.us/mpch/UnidentifiedDetails.asp?id=U0505002|website=Texas Missing Persons Clearinghouse Online Bulletin|publisher=Texas Department of Public Safety|accessdate=28 November 2014|date=2 August 2005}}</ref> The victim's remains were found on a ranch along State Highway 51. He could have died as early as 1984, as a coin with that date was found at the site.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Arnette|first1=Mark|title=Unidentified Remains|url=http://www.baldonart.com/forensics/april20_2006.html|website=http://www.baldonart.com/|publisher=Parker County Sheriff's Office|accessdate=28 November 2014}}</ref> The boy was a white male but may have had black ancestry. Because only some bones were located, his height and weight could not be estimated. His torso, along with one or both hands and limbs, was not recovered.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 4485|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/4485|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=28 November 2014|date=15 October 2008}}</ref> The victim had received dental care, as fillings were found in his teeth. He had short brown hair and wore two gray jackets, one made of fleece and the other of cotton.<ref>{{cite web|title=John Doe 1985|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1104373/1#poster|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]]|accessdate=28 November 2014}}</ref> He also wore jockey underwear and jeans. His exact cause of death is unknown, although his death is considered to be a homicide.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File: 299UMTX|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/299umtx.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=28 November 2014}}</ref>

==Bexar County Jane Doe==

{{Main|Ángel Maturino Reséndiz}}

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://doenetwork.org/cases/images/76UFTX.jpg 3D reconstruction of 1986 victim]
}}

On March 26, 1986, a black woman was shot multiple times and left near a railroad. She was between 18 and 25, standing five feet eleven inches tall. The body had gone undiscovered for approximately three weeks to three months. The motive for the murder was apparently an argument. [[Ángel Maturino Reséndiz]], a serial killer, confessed to her murder, claiming he had also killed the woman's boyfriend, whose remains are yet to be found. The woman wore a [[white gold]] ring, a striped blue short skirt, and a flannel jacket, which was also striped. She was believed to have been native to [[Florida]], her first name reported to possibly be Norma. The woman, along with her boyfriend and another victim, has never been identified. Reséndiz apparently killed seventeen others.<ref name="Case File 76UFTX">{{cite web| title= Case File 76UFTX| url= http://doenetwork.org/cases/76uftx.html| publisher= The Doe Network| accessdate= 12 May 2014}}</ref>

{{anchor|Live Oak Doe}}

==Live Oak Doe==

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://doenetwork.org/cases/images/77umtx1.jpg Sketch reconstruction]
}}

A black subject, twenty to thirty years old, who was likely a [[trans woman]] or a [[drag queen]], was pronounced dead after being transported to a hospital when found unresponsive on July 10, 1986, in [[Live Oak, Texas|Live Oak]], [[Houston, Texas|Houston]], [[Harris County, Texas|Harris County]], [[Texas]]. The cause of death was strangulation, which may have been done with pantyhose. The subject was dressed in pink pants, a gray shirt, and a black belt with spikes. A pair of socks was under the shirt, likely used to mimic breasts. A heart tattoo containing a scroll was on one arm, and the victim's fingernails had been painted gold at one point. Four earrings were found in each ear; a ring with a clear stone, a ring without a stone, a silver chain, and two gold-colored necklaces were also found. The victim may have had a drug history, as needle marks were visible on the arms.<ref name="Unidentified Decedent Flier">{{cite web|title=Unidentified Decedent Flier|url=http://www.harriscountytx.gov/CmpDocuments/21/UDF%202014/1986-07-10-4174.pdf|publisher=Harris County Institute of Forensic Sciences|accessdate=12 July 2014|date=20 May 2014}}</ref><ref name="Case File 77UMTX">{{cite web|title=Case File 77UMTX|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/77umtx.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=12 July 2014}}</ref>

{{anchor|Collin County John Doe}}

==Collin County John Doe==

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://api.missingkids.org/photographs/NCMU1184331c1.jpg Digital reconstruction]
| image2 = [http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/images/54UMTXTat.jpg Tattoo]
| image3 = [http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/images/54UMTXBelt.jpg Belt buckle]
}}

A Hispanic male between fifteen and twenty-five was found stabbed to death on December 15, 1988, in [[Collin County, Texas]]. He had died a day before his body was found abandoned in a culvert. He wore a motorcyclist's jacket and a white and gray striped shirt, along with corduroy jeans, loafers, and a belt with a multi-colored buckle. He had a tattoo on his arm of the letters "RYA" inside a heart with an arrow through it, possibly representing a significant other or a family member. He was found wearing a watch, a bracelet, and two rubber rings. He was relatively short for a male, being five feet to five feet one inch tall. In his pockets, chap stick, a package of cigarettes, and a disposable lighter were found.<ref name="Case File 54UMTX">{{cite web|title=Case File 54UMTX|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/54umtx.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=12 July 2014}}</ref><ref name="John Doe 1988">{{cite web|title=John Doe 1988|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1184331/1#poster|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]]|accessdate=12 July 2014}}</ref>

{{anchor|Corona Girl}}
=="Corona Girl"==

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [https://www.dps.texas.gov/mpch_images/final/U8910001a.jpg Sketch]
| image2 = [https://www.dps.texas.gov/mpch_images/final/U8910001b.jpg Shirt]
}}

On September 25, 1989, the remains of a female aged 18-24 was located in Williamson County, Texas along Interstate 35. She was about 5'2" tall at a weight between 110 and 120 pounds. Her ears were pierced, but only one earring was recovered. The victim also wore a necklace containing a white bead in the center, surrounded by two gold-colored beads on either side. She wore a white shirt with the words "Cinco De Corona" with the bottom cut into fringe, leading to her nickname, black pants a shirt cut into a bra with the words "American Legends" bearing a Native American design. She wore bikini panties and no shoes. The victim was shot to death.<ref>{{cite web |title=74UFTX |url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/74uftx.html |website=www.doenetwork.org |publisher=[[The Doe Network]] |accessdate=12 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref>

{{anchor|Harris County Jane Doe (1989)}}

==Harris County Jane Doe (1989)==
[[File:96UFTX Reconstruction 001b.jpg|thumb|150px|left|1989 Harris County Jane Doe]]

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://api.missingkids.org/photographs/NCMU1184610c1.jpg NCMEC reconstruction]
| image2 = [http://doenetwork.org/cases/images/96uftx1.jpg 2D reconstruction]
}}

Approximately eight to ten hours after her death, a Hispanic female was located on Westheimer Street, in Houston, Harris County, Texas on December 29, 1989.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jane Houston|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1184610/1#poster|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]]|accessdate=8 November 2014}}</ref> She was five feet four inches and weighed 161 pounds; she was between nineteen and twenty-five, although she could have been up to thirty-five.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 2171|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/2171|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=8 November 2014|date=1 July 2008}}</ref> The victim wore black pants, socks and shoes as well as a white bra, panties, pullover and socks. Her hair was black and curly, approximately twenty inches long. Her eyes were also brown.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 96UFTX|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/96uftx.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=8 November 2014}}</ref> A piece of paper was found at the scene that was written by hand containing some sort of schedule.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sanchez|first1=Luke M.|title=Unidentified Decedent Notice|url=http://www.harriscountytx.gov/CmpDocuments/21/Unidentified%20Decedent%20Fliers/1989-12-29-8294.pdf|publisher=Harris County Police Depaqrtment|accessdate=8 November 2014|date=15 April 2011}}</ref> The woman had been shot at close range in the head. After her body remained unidentified, she was buried in an unmarked grave in a potter's field.<ref>{{cite news|last1=George|first1=Cindy|title=An unsolved murder from the 1980s stirs Houston cold case investigators|url=http://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/houston-texas/houston/article/An-unsolved-murder-from-the-1980s-stirs-Houston-11291523.php|accessdate=29 August 2017|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|date=15 July 2017}}</ref>

=="Lavender Doe"==
{{main|Lavender Doe}}

A young adult who was found burning in [[Kilgore, Texas]] on October 29, 2006. Her nickname originated from the purple sweater that she wore.<ref>{{cite web|title=Who is Lavender Doe?|url=http://www.ctcoldcases.com/texas.html|website=ct.coldcases.com|accessdate=31 July 2014}}</ref>

{{anchor|Kendall County Jane Doe}}

==Kendall County Jane Doe==

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://letsfindthem.files.wordpress.com/2013/01/kendall-jane-doe.jpg Sketch]
}}

A female between seventeen and twenty-six was discovered in [[Kendall County, Texas]], on March 6, 2010. The victim's race was either Hispanic or Caucasian, possibly being a mix of both. Examination revealed that she had had a large amount of dental work as well as a previous [[open heart surgery]]. Deformities were also present on the feet. She had died between one year and a decade prior to the discovery.<ref name="Hot Case 2400">{{cite web| title=1341UFTX| url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/1341uftx.html| publisher=The Doe Network| accessdate=26 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=Kendall County Jane Doe Discovered On March 6, 2010| url=http://letsfindthem.wordpress.com/2013/01/09/kendall-county-jane-doe-discovered-on-march-6-2010/| accessdate=26 April 2014}}</ref>

{{anchor|South Padre Island Jane Doe}}

==South Padre Island Jane Doe==

{{for|the victim found in 1980|Lime Lady}}

[[File:South Padre Island Jane Doe.jpg|thumb|150px|Reconstruction of the South Padre Island Jane Doe]]

The decomposed remains of a Hispanic woman were found on a beach, scavenged by coyotes, on October 10, 2012, in South Padre Island, Cameron County, Texas. The victim's body was likely exposed due to changes with water levels on the beach. The woman had been dead from one to several weeks before her remains were discovered.<ref>{{cite news|title=Woman's body found buried on South Padre Island|url=http://www.valleycentral.com/news/story.aspx?id=811545#.Va2DAvlVhHw|accessdate=20 July 2015|work=Action News 4|agency=Valley Central|date=10 October 2012}}</ref> The sand above the body had been "covered with lime," possibly to speed decomposition or plant growth, likely as a way to prevent the body from being found or identified. Her height was estimated to be four feet ten to five feet two inches tall and her weight at about 95 to 120 pounds. She was middle-aged, approximately forty-two to fifty-five, at the time of death.<ref name=gerber>{{cite news|last1=Gerber|first1=Tim|title=FBI hopes 3D facial reconstruction will help ID slain woman|url=http://www.ksat.com/content/pns/ksat/news/2014/11/20/info-sought-in-2012-slaying-of--jane-doe-.html|accessdate=20 July 2015|work=KSAT News 12|publisher=ABC|date=20 November 2015}}</ref> One or more of the female's limbs were not found with the body, as they were likely carried away by animals. A distinctive feature about this female was that she had her make-up permanently tattooed on her eyebrows, eyelids and lips. Her ears had also been pierced.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 10708|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/10708|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=20 July 2015|date=24 October 2012}}</ref> She was clothed, wearing a dark top, multicolored shorts with star decorations and bikini underwear, along with a sanitary pad. The woman's death is considered to be due to foul play and a "suspicious" white-colored "powder" was found on the face region.<ref>{{cite web|title=South Padre Island Jane Doe|url=http://www.hellbeasts.com/?p=8911|website=Hellbeasts|accessdate=20 July 2015|date=9 March 2015}}</ref> Since her discovery, a three-dimensional reconstruction and a sketch have been created of the victim.<ref name=gerber/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Ty|title=Authorities still searching for ID on woman found dead on Islan|url=http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/news/local/article_c79fa3c0-d4fd-11e2-b987-001a4bcf6878.html|accessdate=20 July 2015|work=Brownsville Herald|date=14 June 2014}}</ref>

