{{Orphan|date=July 2014}}
'''Nicholas Alan Clatterbuck'''<ref name="Jul 89">{{cite news|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/57131/3-KILLERS-IN-YOUTH-SYSTEM-5-CONVICTED-AS-ADULTS.html|title=3 Killers in Youth System; 5 Convicted as Adults|author=<!--Staff article, no byline-->|newspaper=[[Deseret News]]|publisher=[[Deseret Digital Media]]|location=Salt Lake City|date=29 Jul 1989|accessdate=8 Oct 2018}}</ref> is an American murderer. He was a 15-year-old juvenile living in a foster home with his [[Foster care|foster parents]] and their children in [[Utah County, Utah|Utah County]], [[Utah]], [[United States]].
==Description== On February 28, 1984, Clatterbuck had some disagreements with the foster parents, resulting in Clatterbuck shooting the foster father 16 times, killing him. He then proceeded to shoot the foster mother several times and stabbed her, resulting in her death. The state decided to prosecute Clatterbuck as an adult.
Clatterbuck was represented by attorney [[Michael D. Esplin]] throughout the juvenile court process where it was determined that he should be tried as an adult in the adult court system. He appealed this determination through the [[Utah Supreme Court]], but his appeal was denied and it was ruled once again that he could be tried as an adult.
The state charged Clatterbuck with capital homicide charges, which carried the death penalty.<ref>Case Number: 700p.2d1076.</ref> Esplin represented Clatterbuck in those proceedings, which ultimately resulted in a plea deal, where the death penalty was taken off the table, and Clatterbuck pleaded to two homicide charges resulting in a sentence of 5 to life in the [[Utah State Prison]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://corrections.utah.gov|title=Utah Department of Corrections|website=corrections.utah.gov|accessdate=21 Jul 2014}}</ref>
In 1989, Clatterbuck graduated from high school prison and was named "outstanding student for the year."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/49118/56-SALUTED-AT-PRISON-GRADUATION-CEREMONY.html|title=56 Saluted at Prison Graduation Ceremony| |last=Van Leer|first=Twila|newspaper=[[Deseret News]]|publisher=[[Deseret Digital Media]]|location=Salt Lake City|date=1 Jun 1989|accessdate=8 Oct 2018}}</ref><ref name="Jul 89"/>
